Hi,

Rather than removing the optimization, or doing something more complex, I kept the logic and just found a way to trick the libxml2 into letting several text nodes, it generates byte to byte the same result as before, with a speedup of 85 times faster here.

Here is the patch based on commit 1db044d91d19:
```
--- libxslt-1db044d91d19/libxslt/transform.c	2019-11-15 12:08:53.000 +0100
+++ libxslt-1db044d91d19m/libxslt/transform.c	2019-12-16 17:01:20.000 +0100
@@ -859,7 +859,19 @@
 	ctxt->lasttuse += len;
 	target->content[ctxt->lasttuse] = 0;
     } else {
-	xmlNodeAddContent(target, string);
+        // if we are in the context of a "text output" document, it is preferable
+        // to lose some memory rather than attempting to "append", else we finish
+        // with O(n^2) behaviour which is catastrophic on big files
+	if (ctxt->type == XSLT_OUTPUT_TEXT)
+    {
+        xmlNodePtr old = xmlNewChild(target->parent, NULL, "text", NULL);
+        target = xmlNewText(string);
+        xmlReplaceNode(old, target);
+    }
+    else
+    {
+        xmlNodeAddContent(target, string);
+    }
 	ctxt->lasttext = target->content;
 	len = xmlStrlen(target->content);
 	ctxt->lasttsize = len;
```

when I do, "make tests" I get errors though, so there is maybe some adjustments to do.

Best regards
Armel

